Project: Data Analysis - Investigate a Dataset¶

Dataset: TMDB Movies¶

Introduction¶

TMDB Movies is a dataset that contains all the information about 5000+ movies. it summarizes the movie's related data like budgte of the movie, revenue, release_date, release_year, and other things, my intention from this dataset is to make a complete analysis over the movies and get interesting results about movie industry for the last 20 years.

this dataset comes from Kaggle's TMDB 5000 Movie Dataset

Questions¶

  1. What are the top movies of the best revenue and budget?
  2. What are the properties of the highest revenue movies?
  3. How much did the companies win over the years?
  4. Which genre is the most watched?

My Intention is to achieve that by going through these stages of analysis:

  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions
  • Limitations

Quick Observations¶

Looking at our data and with a previous look at the documentations of the dataset on Kaggle, we can conclude that:

  • We have two ids that serve as identifiers
  • We have the popularity column given as a metric that is based on (Box Office Review, Appeal, Hours of watching, likes and dislikes.....etc)
  • We have columns for categorical data (original_title, cast, homepage, director, tagline, keywords, overview, production_companies, genres)
  • We have columns for numerical data (budget, revenue, release_year, release_date, budget_adj, revenue_adj, runtime)
  • budget, revenue, _adj columns are put in USD Dollar
  • _adj columns are put adjusted to the inflation in 2010
  • cast, genres and production companies names are given separated by |
  • we have a date and a year.

We can get rid of:

  • keywords, imdb_id, id, release_date, tagline, overview because we wouldn't get any results from them.

Data Cleaning¶

So, after we took a brief look on our data, we can say that we're dealing with:

  • We have a few missing values in (imdb_id, cast, hompage, director, tagline, keywords, overview, genres, production_companies)
  • We have some wrong datatypes in (release_date)
  • We have some columns their values are separated by |
  • There's a huge number of outliers in this dataset (We can't use the mean)
  • There's some zero values in the dataset (budget_adj, budget, revenue, revenue_adj)
  • We have to correct the inflation factor in the _adj columns

Missing Values¶

Dealing with missing values is a bit tricky, why!?, because we have different sceanrios, if the missing values regarding a certain column exceeds 10% of our data, then we can use remove the entire column, if the data doesn't exceed 10% only, then We can remove the rows that contains the missing values, we can also fill missing values that doesn't exceed 10% with a numerical value or by random filling or we can make a default value for missing values.

In short, our solution will depend on the amount of missing values in columns.

To address this problem and to prevent repeating the same process, I created a function that does all of that for us and returns the variable by the name you want.

In [18]:
# function to split columns of a dataframe and return the column need if specified
def split_col_to(var_name, col_to_split, char, col_name, col_needed=0):
    # Create a variable with name
    globals()[var_name] = col_to_split
    
    # Splitting the production_companies column into new columns
    globals()[var_name] = globals()[var_name].str.split(char, expand=True)
    
    # remove additional columns and store them into a dataframe
    globals()[var_name] = pd.DataFrame(globals()[var_name][col_needed])
    
    # rename first column
    globals()[var_name].rename(columns={0: col_name}, inplace=True)

This function takes:

  • var_name: variable's name to be used after the function is initialized
  • col_to_split: the col of the dataframe you want to split
  • char: the character you want to split the col depending on
  • col_name: the column's name because you get a column's name of 0 as default, so you want to rename it to be used logically
  • col_needed: the index of the column you want from the new dataframe
In [19]:
# Apply the function on the (genre, cast, production_companies) columns
split_col_to('cast', df['cast'], "|", 'actor', 0)
split_col_to('production_companies', df['production_companies'], "|", 'production_company', 0)
split_col_to('genres', df['genres'], "|", 'genre', 0)

To address this problem, we can do a random fill over all the zero values with a measure of center, but when it comes to revenue and budget, we can't use the mean, because obviously, we have a lot of outliers, so, we have no choice but to use the median, because it's the least number affected by outliers and skewness.

So, if we want to get a good value to fill randomly, we have to fill with the mean of the non-outlier values (trimmed mean)

In [27]:

revenue_md = revenue_md.mean()

Set inflation factor¶

We now need to set a correct inflation factor to the dataset, because some values are bigger than other in the adjusted columns, so, we need to correct that mistake somehow, and according to the dataset as its values are in dollars, and according to economy resources like Google Trends, US Inflation Calc. we have that USD dollar has an increasing value over time.

Going into these resources, it appears that the inflation factor in 2010, is changing and growing from year to year, but, we have to consider that each year has its own inflation factor, so we can't miss with the values that already in the table, we just need to correct those that are less compared to the original values

So, we have the The Federal Bank of Minnepolis to help us out, by looking at that website we have that $1 now costs $1.40 in the 2010. but, each year has its own rate as we said, so, we need to sort our wrong values and grab each group separately

We should highlight on the fact that the adjustement had been done on the movies even the 2015 ones but if we get the inflation factor in those years, we will find that it's only normal for some values to be smaller than original ones because the buying power of the 2015 ones will decrease compared to the 2010, if we had 100 dollars in 2010 it will be 92 dollars in 2015

After we got the wrong values, and it appears to be at least over 50% of the table but, we can say that if we wanna correct values we need to group them by year, and we also need to collect at least the average factors for the last 50 years

Conclusions¶

And now, After we finished asking questions about the dataset, for now, I wanna insist on the probability of asking more questions and that data analysis is an endless process by itself, so, we can never say we've finished the EDA or Data Wrangling.

After a good analysis on the dataset, we can say that the dataset was about a bunch of movies with a detailed information included about each movie.

We learned a good thing or two about movie industry and got a good insight about the market and movie industry specifically, and the brief looking at revenue and budget gave us good impressions on investing in movies

  • It appears to be that our data revolves around many categorical data and four main numerical ones, and by using those key values we could get interesting information about the movies from profit, inflation, and lose, and and everything else.
  • categorical data helped us in grouping numerical data whether by counting nor by summing them
  • We can say that the high revenue movies have a good a popular genre and a good company, and that means movie industry doesn't depend on certain actor or money to gain popularity
  • rate of movies production appears to be related to revenue rate as it increases
  • the top genre watched is (Drama, Comedy, Action, Sci-Fi)
  • Inflation affected movie industry because dollar buying power changes over time and that increases the revenue even more
  • Long runtime affects the movie greatly as the highest movies in watching are withing runtime average (1.5hrs - 3hrs)

Limitations¶

Of course I'd highlight that we could've completed doing the analysis if we had more information about the dataset that wasn't mentioned before

  • production companies had many null values which left us with no choice but to remove 10% of it and lead to a great loss of data
  • We needed a location of production like a region or something, like US, India, Japan and something
  • We needed the movie type, is it a series, a special, or a movie
  • Is the movie a part of a series or not
  • We needed a category of the movie (Hollywood, Bollywood, Egyptian, Anime and other things)
  • A lot of zero value lead to hindrances in the analysis because filling data randomly is a thing and getting correct data is more accurate, and we had to do it because it is over 40% of the data, so, we needed to fill it somehow and deleting it wasn't an option.
